{{for|the Prussian revolutionary nobleman known as Anacharsis|Jean-Baptiste du Val-de-Grâce, baron de Cloots}}
[[Image:Anacharsis.jpg|right|thumb|18th-century portrait, based on an ancient [[engraved gem]].]]
'''Anacharsis''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|æ|n|ə|ˈ|k|ɑr|s|ɪ|s}}; {{lang-grc|Ἀνάχαρσις}}) was a [[Scythians|Scythian]] philosopher who travelled from his homeland on the northern shores of the [[Black Sea]] to [[Athens]] in the early 6th century BC and made a great impression as a forthright, outspoken "[[barbarian]]". Reputedly a forerunner of the [[Cynicism (philosophy)|Cynics]], none of his works has survived.

